        "Notice two things. First, all three ACF plots show no significant spikes at lags $h \\geq 1$: the autocorrelations are statistically indistinguishable from zero, confirming that all three are white noise. Second, the ARCH(1) time plot shows visible clustering — stretches of large fluctuations and stretches of smaller ones. This structure is real but lives in the second moment (variance), not the first, so it is invisible to the ACF.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Autocovariance and Autocorrelation Functions {#sec-acvf}\n",
        "\n",
        "## Measuring Temporal Dependence\n",
        "\n",
        "Now that we understand what it means for a series to have no temporal dependence (white noise), we are ready to characterize processes that do. The central tool is the autocovariance function.\n",
        "\n",
        "Recall from introductory statistics that the covariance between two random variables $X$ and $Y$ measures the degree to which they move together linearly: $\\text{Cov}(X, Y) = \\mathbb{E}[(X - \\mu_X)(Y - \\mu_Y)]$. For a time series, we are interested in how much the series at time $t$ co-moves with its own past — specifically, with its value at time $t-h$.\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Autocovariance Function\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Definition 1.5 — Autocovariance Function (ACVF)\n",
        "\n",
        "For a weakly stationary process $\\{y_t\\}$ with mean $\\mu$, the **autocovariance function** (ACVF) at lag $h$ is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\gamma(h) = \\text{Cov}(y_t, y_{t-h}) = \\mathbb{E}[(y_t - \\mu)(y_{t-h} - \\mu)]$$\n",
        "\n",
        "By weak stationarity, this quantity depends only on the lag $h$, not on the time index $t$.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "Several properties of the ACVF follow immediately from the definition.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Property 1: Symmetry.** $\\gamma(h) = \\gamma(-h)$ for all $h$. The covariance between today and $h$ periods ago equals the covariance between today and $h$ periods hence. The ACVF is an even function.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Property 2: Maximum at zero.** $|\\gamma(h)| \\leq \\gamma(0)$ for all $h$. The variance of the process — $\\gamma(0) = \\sigma^2$ — is always at least as large in absolute value as any autocovariance. This follows from the Cauchy-Schwarz inequality.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Property 3: Positive semidefiniteness.** For any finite collection of lags and any real coefficients $a_1, \\ldots, a_k$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\sum_{i=1}^{k}\\sum_{j=1}^{k} a_i a_j \\gamma(t_i - t_j) \\geq 0$$\n",
        "\n",
        "This constrains the shape of the ACVF: not every function can be an autocovariance function.\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Autocorrelation Function\n",
        "\n",
        "The autocovariance has units — if $y_t$ is measured in billions of dollars, $\\gamma(h)$ is in billions-of-dollars-squared — which makes it hard to compare across series or across lags. Normalizing by the variance gives a dimensionless quantity.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Definition 1.6 — Autocorrelation Function (ACF)\n",
        "\n",
        "For a weakly stationary process $\\{y_t\\}$, the **autocorrelation function** (ACF) at lag $h$ is:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\rho(h) = \\frac{\\gamma(h)}{\\gamma(0)} = \\frac{\\text{Cov}(y_t, y_{t-h})}{\\text{Var}(y_t)}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "By construction, $\\rho(0) = 1$ and $|\\rho(h)| \\leq 1$ for all $h$.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "The shape of the ACF reveals the temporal structure of the series:\n",
        "\n",
        "- **Slowly decaying ACF:** long memory or a trend; signature of nonstationarity.\n",
        "- **Geometrically decaying ACF:** autoregressive structure.\n",
        "- **Sinusoidal ACF:** periodic or seasonal component.\n",
        "- **ACF cuts off sharply after lag $q$:** moving average process of order $q$.\n",
        "- **ACF indistinguishable from zero at all lags:** white noise.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Estimating the ACF from Data\n",
        "\n",
        "We estimate the autocovariance from the observed series $y_1, \\ldots, y_T$ using the **sample autocovariance**:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\hat{\\gamma}(h) = \\frac{1}{T} \\sum_{t=h+1}^{T} (y_t - \\bar{y})(y_{t-h} - \\bar{y})$$\n",
        "\n",
        "where $\\bar{y} = T^{-1}\\sum_{t=1}^{T} y_t$. Note the divisor is $T$, not $T-h$, even though only $T-h$ terms appear in the sum. Using $T$ ensures positive semidefiniteness of the sample ACVF matrix. The **sample ACF** is then $\\hat{\\rho}(h) = \\hat{\\gamma}(h) / \\hat{\\gamma}(0)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "Under the null hypothesis that $\\{y_t\\}$ is white noise, the sample autocorrelations are approximately normally distributed with mean zero and variance $1/T$ for large $T$, giving the standard 95% confidence bands:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\pm \\frac{1.96}{\\sqrt{T}}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## A Caution on ACF Interpretation\n",
        "\n",
        "The confidence bands assume the true process is white noise. When the ACF shows a clear pattern — slow decay, oscillation, seasonal spikes — interpret the shape as a whole rather than testing each lag individually.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# The Partial Autocorrelation Function {#sec-pacf}\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Problem with the ACF Alone\n",
        "\n",
        "The ACF conflates the direct effect of $y_{t-h}$ on $y_t$ with indirect effects transmitted through intermediate lags. Consider a series where $y_t$ is directly influenced only by $y_{t-1}$: $y_t = \\phi y_{t-1} + \\varepsilon_t$. Because $y_{t-1}$ is correlated with $y_{t-2}$, and $y_{t-2}$ with $y_{t-3}$, the ACF will show nonzero autocorrelations at all lags — not just lag 1.\n",
        "\n",
        "The **partial autocorrelation function** (PACF) isolates the direct relationship. It asks: once we account for the intermediate observations $y_{t-1}, \\ldots, y_{t-h+1}$, how much additional correlation remains between $y_t$ and $y_{t-h}$?\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Partial Autocorrelation via Partial Regression\n",
        "\n",
        "The partial autocorrelation at lag $h$, denoted $\\alpha(h)$, is the coefficient on $y_{t-h}$ in the **population OLS regression** of $y_t$ on its $h$ most recent lags:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$y_t = \\phi_{h,1} y_{t-1} + \\phi_{h,2} y_{t-2} + \\cdots + \\phi_{h,h} y_{t-h} + \\varepsilon_t^{(h)}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The PACF at lag $h$ is the last coefficient: $\\alpha(h) = \\phi_{h,h}$. It measures the marginal contribution of $y_{t-h}$ after all shorter lags have already been included.\n",
        "\n",
        "The first two lags are instructive:\n",
        "\n",
        "**Lag 1.** No intermediate observations to control for: $\\alpha(1) = \\rho(1)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Lag 2.** After removing the effect of $y_{t-1}$ from both $y_t$ and $y_{t-2}$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\alpha(2) = \\frac{\\rho(2) - \\rho(1)^2}{1 - \\rho(1)^2}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Lag $h$.** The general case is computed via the **Yule-Walker equations**:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\alpha(h) = \\frac{\\rho(h) - \\sum_{j=1}^{h-1} \\phi_{h-1,j}\\,\\rho(h-j)}{1 - \\sum_{j=1}^{h-1}\\phi_{h-1,j}\\,\\rho(j)}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "In practice, software handles this recursion automatically.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Definition 1.7 — Partial Autocorrelation Function (PACF)\n",
        "\n",
        "The **partial autocorrelation function** (PACF) at lag $h$ is the coefficient $\\alpha(h) = \\phi_{h,h}$ on $y_{t-h}$ in the population OLS regression of $y_t$ on $(y_{t-1}, \\ldots, y_{t-h})$. It measures the linear dependence between $y_t$ and $y_{t-h}$ after removing the linear influence of all intermediate lags.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Interpreting the PACF: The Diagnostic Table\n",
        "\n",
        "| Process | ACF | PACF |\n",
        "|---------|-----|------|\n",
        "| AR($p$) | Decays to zero (geometrically or oscillating) | Cuts off sharply after lag $p$ |\n",
        "| MA($q$) | Cuts off sharply after lag $q$ | Decays to zero |\n",
        "| ARMA($p$,$q$) | Decays to zero | Decays to zero |\n",
        "| White noise | Zero at all lags | Zero at all lags |\n",
        "| Random walk | Decays very slowly | Large spike only at lag 1 |\n",
        "\n",
        ": ACF and PACF patterns for common time series processes {#tbl-acfpacf}\n",
        "\n",
        "The AR($p$) result follows directly from the partial regression interpretation: only the $p$ most recent lags directly influence $y_t$, so the PACF is exactly zero at all lags greater than $p$.\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "# Testing for Stationarity: The Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test {#sec-adf}\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Unit Root Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "The most widely used formal test for stationarity is the **Augmented Dickey-Fuller (ADF) test**, which tests for the presence of a **unit root**. To understand what this means, consider the random walk:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$y_t = y_{t-1} + \\varepsilon_t, \\qquad \\varepsilon_t \\sim WN(0, \\sigma^2)$$\n",
        "\n",
        "Starting from $y_0$, we have $y_t = y_0 + \\sum_{s=1}^{t} \\varepsilon_s$. The variance grows without bound — $\\text{Var}(y_t) = t\\sigma^2$ — so the process is clearly nonstationary. The hallmark of a random walk is that shocks are **permanent**: a positive shock today shifts $y_t$ up, and it never returns to its previous level.\n",
        "\n",
        "## From the Random Walk to the AR(1)\n",
        "\n",
        "Generalizing to $y_t = \\phi y_{t-1} + \\varepsilon_t$ and subtracting $y_{t-1}$ from both sides with $\\delta = \\phi - 1$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = \\delta y_{t-1} + \\varepsilon_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The unit root null is $H_0: \\delta = 0$ ($\\phi = 1$); the stationary alternative is $H_1: \\delta < 0$ ($\\phi < 1$).\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Basic Dickey-Fuller Test\n",
        "\n",
        "The **Dickey-Fuller test** estimates:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\beta t + \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "and tests $H_0: \\delta = 0$ against $H_1: \\delta < 0$. Three specifications exist:\n",
        "\n",
        "| Specification | Regression | Use when... |\n",
        "|---------------|-----------|-------------|\n",
        "| No constant, no trend | $\\Delta y_t = \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$ | Series has no drift, zero mean |\n",
        "| Constant only | $\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$ | Series may have a non-zero mean |\n",
        "| Constant and trend | $\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\beta t + \\delta y_{t-1} + u_t$ | Series may have a linear trend under $H_1$ |\n",
        "\n",
        ": Dickey-Fuller specification choices {#tbl-df-specs}\n",
        "\n",
        "The critical values are **not** standard $t$-distribution values. Under $H_0$, $y_{t-1}$ is integrated, giving the OLS estimator $\\hat{\\delta}$ a non-standard left-skewed asymptotic distribution — the **Dickey-Fuller distribution**. Using standard $t$ critical values would severely under-reject the unit root null.\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Augmented Dickey-Fuller Test\n",
        "\n",
        "The basic DF test assumes $u_t$ is white noise. The **ADF test** adds lagged differences to absorb serial correlation:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\Delta y_t = \\alpha + \\beta t + \\delta y_{t-1} + \\sum_{j=1}^{p} \\psi_j \\Delta y_{t-j} + u_t$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The null remains $H_0: \\delta = 0$, and the test statistic is the $t$-ratio on $\\hat{\\delta}$:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{ADF statistic} = \\frac{\\hat{\\delta}}{\\text{se}(\\hat{\\delta})}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "The augmentation lags do not change the asymptotic distribution under $H_0$.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Choosing the Lag Length $p$\n",
        "\n",
        "**Information criteria.** Select $p$ to minimize AIC or BIC:\n",
        "\n",
        "$$\\text{AIC}(p) = \\log\\hat{\\sigma}^2_p + \\frac{2(p+k)}{T} \\qquad \\text{BIC}(p) = \\log\\hat{\\sigma}^2_p + \\frac{\\log(T)(p+k)}{T}$$\n",
        "\n",
        "**General-to-specific (GETS).** Start with $p_{\\max} = \\lfloor 12(T/100)^{1/4} \\rfloor$ (Schwert rule). Drop the last lag if insignificant and repeat until a significant lag is found or $p = 0$.\n",
        "\n",
        "We use AIC-based selection throughout this textbook.\n",
        "\n",
        "## Interpreting ADF Results\n",
        "\n",
        "The output consists of: (1) the **test statistic** — more negative means stronger evidence against the unit root; (2) the **p-value** — below 0.05 leads to rejection; (3) **critical values** at 1%, 5%, and 10%.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-warning}\n",
        "## Two Common Mistakes\n",
        "\n",
        "**Mistake 1:** Failing to reject $H_0$ is not evidence for a unit root. The ADF has low power against near-unit-root alternatives.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Mistake 2:** The specification matters. Always inspect the time plot before choosing whether to include a constant and/or trend.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "The complement of the ADF — where the null is stationarity — is the **KPSS test**. Running both and checking for consistency is good practice.\n",
