      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "The results confirm what the time plots and ACF/PACF analysis suggested. **Log Real GDP** and **Log CPI** both fail to reject the unit root null — the test statistics are close to zero, far less negative than the critical values, and p-values are large. Both level series are nonstationary $I(1)$ processes.\n",
        "\n",
        "**GDP Growth** rejects the unit root decisively: the test statistic is strongly negative, well below the 1% critical value, with a p-value essentially zero. **Year-on-Year Inflation** rejects the unit root at the 5% level, though the literature on inflation persistence is extensive precisely because inflation can behave like a near-$I(1)$ process over certain subperiods.\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note}\n",
        "## Summary of Integration Orders\n",
        "\n",
        "Log GDP and log CPI are $I(1)$: nonstationary in levels, stationary in first differences. GDP growth and inflation are $I(0)$: stationary. This is a classic and well-established finding in macroeconometrics that motivates essentially all the model specifications we develop in this course.\n",
        ":::\n",
