        "# Chapter Summary\n",
        "\n",
        "Let us take stock of what we have covered. This chapter has laid the conceptual and technical foundations on which the entire course is built.\n",
        "\n",
        "We began by defining what a time series is and why it is fundamentally different from cross-sectional data: the order of observations matters, dependence is the signal rather than the noise, and we have only one realization of history to work with. We distinguished **forecasting** from prediction and causal inference, clarified the three types of forecasts — point, interval, and density — and introduced the **loss function** as the criterion that determines what the \"best\" forecast means. We were honest about the particular challenges of economic forecasting: structural change, measurement error, the Lucas critique, and reflexivity.\n",
        "\n",
        "We established the language of time series: the time index, frequency, regularity, and core notation — the lag operator $L$, the difference operator $\\Delta$, the information set $\\mathcal{F}_t$, and the autocovariance function $\\gamma(h)$.\n",
        "\n",
        "We defined **stationarity** in its two forms — strict and weak — and argued that weak (covariance) stationarity is the workhorse assumption of the course. Stationarity ensures that time averages converge, model parameters are stable over time, and the spurious regression problem does not arise.\n",
        "\n",
        "We defined **white noise** and distinguished IID noise from weak white noise, using ARCH processes to illustrate that zero autocorrelation does not imply independence.\n",
        "\n",
        "We developed the **ACVF and ACF**, established their key properties, and showed how the shape of the sample ACF reveals the temporal structure of a process. We then derived the **PACF** through the partial regression framework — the coefficient on $y_{t-h}$ in the regression of $y_t$ on all intermediate lags — measuring direct dependence stripped of indirect effects.\n",
        "\n",
        "We derived the **ADF test** from first principles, giving detailed guidance on specification, lag selection, and interpretation.\n",
        "\n",
        "Finally, we applied all tools to US real GDP and CPI: time plots, ACF and PACF analysis, and formal ADF tests. The theory came alive in the data — the slowly decaying ACF of nonstationary level series, the sharp truncation after differencing, and ADF results that formalize the $I(1)$ classification.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Looking ahead.** Chapter 2 introduces the building blocks of parametric time series models: autoregressive (AR) and moving average (MA) processes. Armed with the ACF and PACF diagnostics developed here, we will have the tools to identify, estimate, and interpret these models.\n",
        "\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-note icon=false}\n",
        "## Key Terms\n",
        "\n",
        "**Time series** — A sequence of observations on a variable ordered by time.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Forecasting** — Using information available at time $T$ to form statements about future values $y_{T+h}$.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Point / Interval / Density forecast** — A single number / a range / a full distribution as a forecast.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Loss function** — The criterion by which forecast errors are penalized; determines the optimal forecast.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Lag operator** $L$ — $Ly_t = y_{t-1}$; enables compact algebraic expression of time series models.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Weak stationarity** — Constant mean, constant variance, and autocovariances that depend only on lag, not on time.\n",
        "\n",
        "**White noise** $WN(0,\\sigma^2)$ — Zero mean, constant variance, zero autocovariances at all nonzero lags.\n",
        "\n",
        "**ACVF** $\\gamma(h)$ — $\\text{Cov}(y_t, y_{t-h})$ for a weakly stationary process.\n",
        "\n",
        "**ACF** $\\rho(h)$ — $\\gamma(h)/\\gamma(0)$; the normalized autocovariance.\n",
        "\n",
        "**PACF** $\\alpha(h)$ — Coefficient on $y_{t-h}$ in the OLS regression of $y_t$ on $y_{t-1},\\ldots,y_{t-h}$; measures direct dependence after removing intermediate effects.\n",
        "\n",
        "**Unit root** — A characteristic root equal to 1; implies nonstationarity.\n",
        "\n",
        "**ADF test** — Augmented Dickey-Fuller test for the null hypothesis of a unit root.\n",
        "\n",
        "**$I(1)$** — Nonstationary in levels, stationary in first differences.\n",
        ":::"
